.TH "SANITIZER.ALLOWELEMENT" "3JS" "January 16, 2026" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Sanitizer.allowElement \- Sanitizer: allowElement() method
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]allowElement()\f[B]\f[R] method of the
\f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] interface sets that the specified element is
allowed in the output when the sanitizer is used.
.PP
It can also be used to specify per\-element attribute allow or remove
arrays on \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] instances with an allow configuration.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
allowElement(element)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]element\f[R]
A string indicating the name of the allowed element, or an object with
the following properties:
.RS
.TP
\f[B]name\f[R]
A string containing the name of the element.
.TP
\f[B]namespace\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
A string containing the namespace of the element.
The default namespace is
\f[CR]\(dqhttp://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\(dq\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]attributes\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
An array indicating the attributes to allow on this (allowed) element
when sanitizing HTML.
.RS
.PP
Each attribute can be specified by name (a string), or as an object with
the following properties:
.TP
\f[B]name\f[R]
A string containing the name of the attribute.
.TP
\f[B]namespace\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
A string containing the namespace of the attribute, which defaults to
\f[CR]null\f[R].
.RE
.TP
\f[B]removeAttributes\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
An array indicating the attributes to remove on this (allowed) element
when sanitizing HTML.
.RS
.PP
Each attribute can be specified by name (a string), or as an object with
the following properties:
.TP
\f[B]name\f[R]
A string containing the name of the attribute.
.TP
\f[B]namespace\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
A string containing the namespace of the attribute, which defaults to
\f[CR]null\f[R].
.RE
.RE
.SS Return value
\f[CR]true\f[R] if the operation changed the configuration to allow the
element, and \f[CR]false\f[R] if the configuration was not changed
(usually because the element was already allowed, but potentially
because the change could not be made).
.PP
Note that \f[CR]false\f[R] might be returned if the internal
configuration:
.IP \(bu 2
defines the \f[CR]elements\f[R] array and the element is already present
(it does not need to be added again).
.IP \(bu 2
defines the \f[CR]removeElements\f[R] array and the specified element is
not present (and is hence already not filtered).
.IP \(bu 2
defines the \f[CR]removeElements\f[R] array and attempts to allow an
element with per\-element attributes.
This operation is not supported because in a valid configuration you
can\(cqt have both \f[CR]removeElements\f[R] and \f[CR]elements\f[R]
arrays, and per\-element attributes are added in the \f[CR]elements\f[R]
array.
The call won\(cqt change the configuration and will generate a console
warning.
.SH DESCRIPTION
The \f[CR]allowElement()\f[R] method sets that the specified element is
allowed in the output when the sanitizer is used.
.PP
The method can be used with either an allow configuration or a remove
configuration.
If used with an allow configuration, the specified element is added to
the \f[CR]elements\f[R] array.
If used with a remove configuration, the element is removed from the
\f[CR]removeElements\f[R] array (if present).
If present, it would also be removed from the
\f[CR]replaceWithChildrenElements\f[R] array.
.PP
For example, the following code creates an allow \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R]
that allows \f[CR]<span>\f[R] elements and then calls
\f[CR]allowElement()\f[R] to additionally allow \f[CR]<b>\f[R] elements.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] sanitizer = \f[B]new\f[R] Sanitizer({ elements: [\(dqspan\(dq] });
sanitizer.allowElement(\(dqb\(dq);
.EE
.PP
When using a \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] with an allow configuration you can
also use the method to specify attributes to be allowed or disallowed on
elements of that type.
For example, the following code first creates an allow sanitizer
configuration by specifying the \f[CR]elements\f[R] array (creating a
\f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] with an empty object or no configuration object
would also result in an \(lqallow configuration\(rq).
It then calls \f[CR]allowElement()\f[R] to allow \f[CR]div\f[R]
elements, to allow the \f[CR]class\f[R] attribute on \f[CR]<div>\f[R]
elements, and to remove the \f[CR]lang\f[R] attribute on
\f[CR]<div>\f[R] elements.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] sanitizer = \f[B]new\f[R] Sanitizer({ elements: [\(dqspan\(dq] });
sanitizer.allowElement({
  name: \(dqdiv\(dq,
  attributes: [\(dqclass\(dq],
  removeAttributes: [\(dqlang\(dq],
});
.EE
.PP
If you need both per\-element add\-attribute and remove\-attribute
arrays as shown above, they must be added in a single call to this
method.
If you were to do this in two calls the second call would replace the
element definition added in the first call.
.PP
When using a \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] with a remove configuration, similar
code to add per\-element attribute allow or remove arrays will generate
a console warning and return \f[CR]false\f[R].
This is because internally the sanitizer doesn\(cqt have the
\f[CR]elements\f[R] array required to specify per\-element attributes
and won\(cqt change the configuration.
.PP
\f[B]Bad\f[R]
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// Define Sanitizer with a remove configuration\f[R]
\f[I]// by specifying removeElements in the configuration\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] sanitizer = \f[B]new\f[R] Sanitizer({ removeElements: [] });
\f[I]// Returns false and raises a console warning\f[R]
sanitizer.allowElement({
  name: \(dqdiv\(dq,
  attributes: [\(dqclass\(dq],
  removeAttributes: [\(dqlang\(dq],
});
.EE
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS How to allow elements
This example shows how \f[CR]allowElement()\f[R] is used to add an
element to the sanitizer\(cqs \f[CR]elements\f[R] configuration (the
list of allowed elements).
.SS JavaScript
The code first creates a new \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] object that initially
allows \f[CR]<div>\f[R] and \f[CR]<script>\f[R] elements.
It then calls \f[CR]allowElement()\f[R] to add a \f[CR]<p>\f[R] element
specified as a string parameter, and then again to add a
\f[CR]<span>\f[R] element specified as an object.
We then get and log the configuration.
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// Create sanitizer using SanitizerConfig\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] sanitizer = \f[B]new\f[R] Sanitizer({
  elements: [\(dqdiv\(dq, \(dqscript\(dq],
});

\f[I]// Allow <p> specifying a string\f[R]
sanitizer.allowElement(\(dqp\(dq);

\f[I]// Allow <span> specifying an object\f[R]
sanitizer.allowElement({ name: \(dqspan\(dq });

\f[B]let\f[R] sanitizerConfig = sanitizer.get();
log(JSON.stringify(sanitizerConfig, \f[B]null\f[R], 2));
.EE
.SS Results
The final configuration is logged below.
This includes the original elements (\f[CR]<div>\f[R] and
\f[CR]<script>\f[R]) and the two added with \f[CR]allowElement()\f[R]
(\f[CR]<p>\f[R] and \f[CR]<span>\f[R]).
.SS Allowing elements that are already allowed or removed
This example shows the effect of using \f[CR]allowElement()\f[R] to add
elements that are already allowed, or that are in the configuration as
\(lqto be removed\(rq.
.SS JavaScript
The code first creates a new \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] object that initially
allows \f[CR]<div>\f[R] elements (removing attributes other than
\f[CR]id\f[R]) and also replaced \f[CR]<span>\f[R] elements with any
child elements.
.PP
It then calls \f[CR]allowElement()\f[R], firstly to add a
\f[CR]<div>\f[R] element that removes \f[CR]style\f[R] attributes.
Since the \f[CR]<div>\f[R] element is already allowed, it is removed
from the \f[CR]elements\f[R] configuration and the \f[CR]<div>\f[R]
element definition is appended.
.PP
A \f[CR]<span>\f[R] element is then added to the allow list, which
removes it from the \f[CR]replaceWithChildrenElements\f[R] configuration
list.
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// Create sanitizer using SanitizerConfig\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] sanitizer = \f[B]new\f[R] Sanitizer({
  elements: [{ name: \(dqdiv\(dq, attributes: [{ name: \(dqid\(dq }] }],
  replaceWithChildrenElements: [\(dqspan\(dq],
});

\f[I]// Allow <div> elements.\f[R]
\f[I]// Allow id elements but strip their style attributes\f[R]
sanitizer.allowElement({
  name: \(dqdiv\(dq,
  removeAttributes: [\(dqstyle\(dq],
});

\f[I]// Allow <span> elements\f[R]
sanitizer.allowElement(\(dqspan\(dq);

\f[B]let\f[R] sanitizerConfig = sanitizer.get();
log(JSON.stringify(sanitizerConfig, \f[B]null\f[R], 2));
.EE
.SS Results
The final configuration is logged, and is shown below.
From the log we can see that the original filter for the
\f[CR]<div>\f[R] element has been removed and the new definition
appended to the \f[CR]elements\f[R] list.
Adding the \f[CR]<span>\f[R] element to the \f[CR]elements\f[R] list has
removed it from the \f[CR]replaceWithChildrenElements\f[R] list.
